Section 1: Executive Summary
Problem Statement
Non-engineers (product managers, analysts, marketers) are increasingly responsible for releasing software features. They face three options:
    1. File a ticket — Wait 1–2 weeks for engineering bandwidth
    2. Get complex tool access — Enterprise-grade platforms overwhelm non-technical users
    3. Ask informally — Shadow IT pattern where features bypass governance
The tension is structural: velocity engineers want to ship; governance teams want control. The answer isn't restriction — it's infrastructure with guardrails built in.
Solution
A feature flag lifecycle tool that provides:
    • Self-serve configuration for non-technical stakeholders
    • Coherent UX across CLI (engineers), Dashboard (product), SDK (pipelines)
    • Simulation before deployment — See impact before rolling out
    • Progressive disclosure — Simple defaults, advanced options on demand
What This Demonstrates
This project demonstrates cross-surface UX coherence as a thesis for modern developer tooling. The architecture applies to feature flags, but also to agent governance, data validation, experiment configuration — any lifecycle spanning human designers, developers, and automated pipelines.
Success Criteria
    • Three surfaces (CLI, Dashboard, SDK) share same terminology, colors, and exit codes
    • Non-technical user can configure and deploy without engineering help
    • CI/CD pipeline validates flag changes automatically
    • All design principles from Section 11 are demonstrated in code

