Section 11: Design Rationale & Success Metrics
11.1 Design Principles Index
Every component in this project traces back to one or more of these principles. This table maps principles to where they appear in the codebase.
Principle	Where It Appears	How
Output scannable in 3 seconds	CLI summary table, Dashboard summary card	Top-level verdict visible before any scrolling
Colors functional, not decorative	All surfaces	Green = receive, Red = exclude, Yellow = partial. No accent colors for branding.
Exit codes are the real product	CLI, SDK, CI/CD	Machines read exit codes. Humans read output. Both served.
Suggestions beat diagnoses	CLI error messages, Dashboard form validation, SDK error objects	"Did you mean X?" not "Error: invalid input"
Consistency is the hardest feature	Shared types, color mappings, terminology	Same field names, same colors, same exit codes across all three surfaces
Transparent reasoning beats black boxes	Decision trace tree, rule source links, webhook events with full context	User always knows why a decision was made
Design for explicit role division	Three surfaces mapped to three audiences (human-typing, human-clicking, machine-calling)	Each surface optimized for its consumer, not a generic "one size fits all"
Intentional restraint	Collapsible tree nodes, disabled save button, debounced validation, --quiet flag	Show less by default. Reveal on demand. Hide what shouldn't be seen.
Validate before you compute	Flag editor live validation, form input validation, CLI argument checking	Bad input caught early, never reaches the API
Graceful failure is a feature	404 redirect page, toast notifications, retry logic, timeout handling	Every failure mode has a defined, tested outcome
11.2 Cross-Surface Consistency Matrix
This is the core thesis of the demo. One design language, three surfaces.
Concept	CLI	Dashboard	SDK
Verdict display	Colored table rows	Colored badges (same hex)	exit_code field
Color: receive	\u001b[32m (green)	bg-green-200 (Tailwind green)	N/A (data only)
Color: exclude	\u001b[31m (red)	bg-red-200 (Tailwind red)	N/A (data only)
Color: partial	\u001b[33m (yellow)	bg-yellow-200 (Tailwind yellow)	N/A (data only)
Error terminology	"Flag not found"	"Flag not found"	code: 'FLAG_NOT_FOUND'
Suggestion format	"Did you mean X?" inline	"Tip: Try X" below field	.getFirstSuggestion() method
Summary fields	passed, conflicted, warned	summary.passed, .conflicted, .warned	result.summary.{passed, conflicted, warned}
Timeout default	5000ms	Spinner after 5000ms	timeoutMs: 5000
Retry behavior	Human re-runs command	Human clicks "Retry"	isRetryable() + getRetryDelay()
Flag ID pattern	^[a-z0-9-]+$	^[a-z0-9-]+$	^[a-z0-9-]+$
Why this matters: A product manager who uses the Dashboard in the morning and an engineer who uses the CLI in the afternoon don't have to relearn anything. Colors mean the same thing. Terminology is identical. Mental model transfers.
11.3 Security-Aware UX Decisions
These are UX-level choices — not backend architecture. They demonstrate that the design considers what shouldn't be shown, not just what should.
Decision	Surface	Rationale
API key in GitHub Secrets	CI/CD (Section 7)	Key never appears in code, commits, or logs. Pipeline reads from encrypted store.
Error objects exclude credentials	SDK (Section 6)	FlagApiError contains code, message, and suggestion. Never includes request body or auth headers.
Input validation before submission	Dashboard (Flag Editor)	Flag ID pattern enforced client-side. Invalid input never reaches API.
Disabled save on invalid input	Dashboard (Flag Editor)	Broken configurations cannot be persisted. Prevents downstream impact.
Dropdown for environment selection	Dashboard (Flag Editor)	No free-text environment input. Prevents typos and arbitrary values.
Debounced validation	Dashboard (Flag Editor)	500ms delay prevents rapid-fire API calls from automated input.
Rollout range enforced (0–100)	CLI and Dashboard	Both surfaces validate numeric range before processing.
